{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bindweed_ver02/data/sn83045774/00271744146/1921032401/0723.xml":{"full_text":"45,000 HARVESTER\nMEN WORLD OVER\nGET COT IN WAGES\nSlush From 5 to JO Per Cent.\nIncludes President and\nOffice Hoy.\nFAVOR LOW PAY M EX\nLiving Cost and Business\nOutlook Considered in\nMaking* Move.\n1 ALTON ROAD VACATIONS\nTen Day Layoffs and Reduc\ntion in Working1 Hours\nAre Announced.\nBprciaI Despatch to Tub New \\ntK Heejld.\nChicago. March 28.?Reduction of\nthe number of working\" clays, ten day\n\"vacations\" without pay and retrench\nment moves on the Chicago and Alton\nRailroad. and a stash of from 5 to 20\njier cent. In wages paid to 45,000 em\nployees of the International Harvester\nCompa/iy wero the two outstanding\nfeatures in Chicago's \"reconstruction\"\nmanoeuvres toward \"normalcy\" to-day.\nThe Harvester company's wage re\nductions. according to an announce\nment by the company, will affect every\nemployee of the concern from presi\n<lent to office boy throughout the\n?worldwide organization, and was made\ntifter an analysis of living costs, busi\nres* possibilities ond working condi\ntlCtflS.\nW. Bierd. president of the Alton,\nmaking the announcement of the re\ntrenchment activities of the road, de\nclared that five and six day weeks for\nnil employees. ten day lay offs for all\nemployees below the rank of aupertn-\ntendent, the closing of the Bloomlngton\nshops for ten days and the suspension\ncf ten locnl trains on branch lines were\nmade necessary by the fact that the\nroad at the present time was not earn\ning operating expenses.\nThe announcement explains that the\ninduction of working days rather than\nthe reduction in number of employees\nwas decided on, and that beginning at\nonce clerks tn all departments,\ndraughtsmen, civil engineers, agents,\ndie., will take ten day layoffs.\nShops now running five days a week\nwill continue to run on the present\n?chedule until business picks up, but\ntrackxnen now working five days a\nweek will be restored to six day weeks\non April li>. when the summer mainte\nnance programme will begin.\nThe Harvester <'ornpsny reduction pro\ngramme arranges for the keeping of all\nmen posaibN, but reduction* to all men\nwho arr kept. Employees who received\ntho largest increuses in wages during\nthe war boom are slaled for the most\neevero cuts, while employees who have\nfamilies and those whose wages ad\nvanced only slightly during the war\nperiod will receive minimum cuts wh-jn\npossible.\nCITIZENS PATROL\nARKANSAS RAILROAD\n\nOperation to Be Resumed Un\nder Protection.\nHarrison. Ark.. March 23.?Patrolling\nof the railroad track', and other prop\nerty of the Miasourl and North Arkansas\nRailroid in Carroll. Boone and Searcy\ncounties was begun to-day in accordance\nWith decision reached a mufti m<-l\nJng here jvsterdav to furnish tlv pro\nt 'etlon decla-? by railroad oil1.- ials to\nbe necesanry to op< ration of trnfll\nIn Carroll county memb' rs c f tin\npatrol wer? appoint- 1 special di; uty\ne/ieriffs at the Instruct'on of the county\nJudge. In Bf>one a><<1 other counties\nrlumbers of cltlicna' leagued volunteered\ntheir services and were placed on duty\n?s special officers.\nCm the strength of promisee of pro- j\ntaction General Manager C. A. Phelan\nannounced that operation of Che road\nwould be resumed probably to-morrow of\nFriday, but late to-day it was stated that\nheavy rainfall *m retarding repair work\n?n bridges which were burned, and tha< I\nreoumptlon of traffic might he delayed\nlonger\nThe Boone County Grand Jury to-day\nreturned thirteen Indictments -ifnlnst\nstrike leader-', including several from\nrational headquarter* of tl>?* unions\nwhose men fre on utrlk.' Th# Indi'-t\nnenta, it w?? said, charge th? union\nmen with persuading muterial witnesses\nin a felony rase to leave the county.\nPreacher, Good Worker,\nin Rush; Says Want Ad.\nJX)STON, March 26.?A \"want\nad\" sandwiched between ad\nvertisements for a bookkeeper\nand an automobile repairman in.\nthe \"Male Help Wanted\" col\numns of a Boston evening news\npaper, to-day, called for a min\nister \"between 30 and 40 years\nold. who is a good parish work\ner.\"\nThe advertisement was in\nserted by a \"Universalist church\nestablished over forty years, and\nin excellent financial condition.\"\nParticulars of age, experience\nand salary expected were asked\nof applicants.\nIn a news story on another\npage it was asserted that a \"lib\neral and progressive man\" was\nwanted, not a theologian merely,\nbut \"a preacher of imagination\nand true religious spirit.\" The\nchurch committeemen were said\nto have decided they would not\nwait for the right man to come\nto them, but would seek him\nthrough the classified advertising\ncolumns. The name and locality\nof the church were not disclosed.\nJ\nMARINE ENGINEERS\nGALLED TO STRIKE\nContinued from /?*?rat Phq'\nStation of wartime national agreements\nshould be the first stops. Members of\nthe association are urged by Mr. But\nterworth to wire Judpro R. M. Barton,\nchairman of the United States Railroad\nLabor Board, to this effect.\nA report of the conference held a\nweek ago In Philadelphia by T. De Witt\nCuyler, chairman of the Aiwoelat ion of\nRailway Executives and the head* of\nthe four biff brotherhoods of skilled\nrailroad workers, will be made to-day\nto the standing committee of railway\nexecutives. Wages, working conditions\nand the problem of reglbr.a! boards were\ndiscussed. Further conferences will fol\nlow to-day's meeting.\nATTERBURY HOLDS\nGROUND AT HEARING\nIs Unshaken in Opposition to\nAny Railroad Rnlos Na\ntional in Scope.\nChicago, March 25.?Cross-examlna\ntlori of high railroad officials by labor\nunion representatives brfor\" the Rail\nroar! Labor Board v-ns completed to-day\nwhen Gen. W. W. Atterbury, vice-presi\ndent of the pfnnsylvanla, finished his\nthird >dav of testimony.\nTo-day's hearing found Gen. Atter\nbury etill unshaken In his opposition to\nany railroad rules which were national\nIn scope despite nttemp's of Mr. Walsh\nto olte some rule which the Pennsyl\nvania official would agree could be ap\nplied nationally with benefit to both\nemployer and employee.\nGen. Atterbury countered by admit\nting that .some principles might l?e (til\nright nationally, but called attention to\nthe distinction between principles and\nrules. He cltcd tho Ten f'ommandments\nus principles.\nMr. Walsh took up the War I^abor\nBoard's principle of n llvlne wage.\n\"Won't you agree that this is a. de\nsirable principle?\" asked he.\n\"Yes, It's a good principle, but it\nwon't apply as a rule,\" answered the\nGeneral.\nGen. Atterbury als\" repeated lii.->\nthat the national agreements\ncaused the roads a los.-. of $300,000.\nannually and sui>mitteJ a table com\npile) by the Association of Kalhoad\nExecutives from Interstate Commerce\nCommission figures, which he said\nproved his contention.\nMr. Walsh challenged the accuracy of\nthe figures and asked how they were\nreached.\n'1 have really grossly understated the\nfigures.\" said Gen. Atterbury. He tlion\nfil. .-i with tfra bosrd a statement which\n-aid ml tin llll'\" payroll >-f tua<irt\n$4,000,000.00#. In 131?. -i, said,\n.20*.*>S# men were employed and in\n!!'2n there rveie 1.43#.488 pM^i? on the\npayrolls, an increase of 239,9<>8. \"This\nincreMM was caus? d by the eight hour\nday, decrease tn production per man and\nIncreased business The total aarnlngs\nin 1917 were $1.010.896.751. or $837.61\nper man. In 1810 the earnings were\n12,444,748,441. or 11,701.90 per man.\n\"The increase in ton miles was 4.4\npor cent In 1920 over 1017. Assuming\nthat tha increase In the number of em\nployees is dlrwtly proportionate to the\nincrease In business, an assumption in\nthe employ es' favor, it would require\n.?^,0J?6 nddltional men to handle tne in\ncn :ise in business. In reality, as 1 have\n-hown, we require 229.P6S additional\nmen. or an ex< at 178.88J crmplt yees\nover -.vhat should have been needed.\nTt-?,e xci men, at the average \"arn\nIng 11,701.20, show an excesn ex\npenditure, consequently. of $800,\n91 l.fiSMO.\"\n?EXPRESS THIEF LOST\nHIS LOOT AT POKER\ni W. A. Hughes, Witness in Con\nspiracy Case, Almost Col\nlapses on Stand.\nFIVE DAYS TESTIFYING\nAdmits Longer He Remain wl\nWith Company the More\nHe Stole.\n\nj Sprcial Despatch to Tic* New lom HauiA\nMacov, Ga., March 23.?At fli'' \"nd of\nrive days on the stand W. A. Hughes,\none of the most Important irttflMw* for\nthe American Railway Rxpress Com\npany in the trial of fifty-three* portions\naccused of conspiracy to steal from the\nUnited States Government, was on the\nverge of a collapse to-day.\nOliver C. HancT>ck, representing H. L?\nRocker, one of the defendants, during\nthe cross-examination asked:\n\"You were not interested with Rooker\nIn any of the transactions, were you?\"\n\"Mr. Hancock, we were all interested\ntogether,\" quifkly replied the witness.\nFollowing Hughe* a dozen witnesses\ntook the stand to tell of shipments they\nI had made on which there was no d<\nlivrry. The reticular articles ?cri>\nbrought into court and wore identified\n>jy 'hese witnesses. The goods, the Qov\nornment showed, had been taken from\nhomes of the defendants, their names\nbeing given In each case.\nWallace Miller, leading counsel for the\ndefence, questioned Hughes for ?n h^ur\nat the opening of court on testimony\nthat he had given conceml;.;? seven of\ni rhe defendants on, the day before, es\nI peclally as to an art squave that Hughes\nj said he had given to M. A_ Sheppard at\nI Albany.\nHo denied he had griven the art 'juare\nas a wedding present. \"I said: 'Sliep.\nthere'H an art square without any\nmarkH,'\" explained the witness. \"He\nsaid: 'Good, I'll take it.'\nA whiskey transaction with the \"Smith\ncrew\" was next gone into. Hughes ;-uifl\nhe had got twenty-four half pints of\ntitle liquor and did not know how many\nConductor Smith or Baggage Master\nSmith obtained. He said he gave some\nto Albei-t Smith, the porter, to s?!l on\nthe train. He declared the portei- wer.t\nthrough the train selling tlie liquor to\npassengers. Asked where tlx\" porter is\ni now the witness replied \"He's dead.\"\ni Morgan Prestwood of Andalusia, Ala..\ntook up the cross-examlnatlan and\nbrought out an admission from- Hui?h>\nI that the longer he stayed with the com\npany the more he stole. Asked to nam\"\nj one Instance where he had hesitated to\n1 steal he said once Floyd Moiris \"per\nwaded him to steal a barrel of pecans\nagainst his wish.\nJud^e E. W. ^Maynard drew from the\ni witness statement that he did not\n1 accumulate money from hiH thefts but\nlost it all In poker games. He said J.\nj L. Johnson taught him how to play.\n\"You did not hesitate to lie when you\nwere stealing, did you?\" the lawyer\nlinked.\n\"We all lied,\" Hughes declared.\nHughes suld he would not lie on any\nof the defendants, \"regardless of what\nbecame of me.\" He denied that he was\n\"framing\" a story, hoplntj thereby lo\nobtRln leniency for'himself.\n\"For six months before mv ar>e*t I\ncould not sleep.\" suid the witness. \"When\nI was arrested I tried to make a clean\nbreast of it.\"\nRe-direct examination took up only\nfive minutes, then identification of re\ncovered stolen property began.\n1BINGHAMTON STRIKING\nPRINTERS 'SATISFIED'\nPublishers Also Report Prog\nress in Struggle.\nBin?ha?cton, March J8.?Binrham\nton'a striking printers to-day issued u\nstatement to the public on the situation\nfrom their viewpoint as It stands at the\npresent. They say that conditions so far\n;ts they are concerned are eminently sat\nisfactory; that the '*Blg six\" Union of\nN'ew York city has sent a Check for\n*1,000 and the Uttca Typographical\nt'nion $S5. That the supply of strifce\nbreakws obtained In Btfighaniton is nm\nfflci' nt to meet requirements and the\nla 11% n^wtpaiKrs ar? thus able to\nprint only a limited amount of advertis\ning; that two members returned to work\nfor the publishers, hut In capacities that\neannot technically be termed desertion,\nand that all others are standing Arm.\nThe publishers declare they are well\nwatisfled with progress being made. That\nj additions to their forces are being re\nceived dally, the site of the papers and\nthe amount of advertising Increased snd\nthat there have been practically no cir\nculation losses as the result of the strike.\n\nSILK MBS BLKCT.\nHopes for hetti r times In the silk in\n1 dustry were expressed yesterday :it ili?\nforty-ninth annual meeting of the SHU\nAssociation of America. James A. Oolrl\nsmlth. s member of the firm of He*-;\nGoldsmith A Co. and of the Board of\nDirector* of the Importers' and Trader\nNational Hank, was elected president\n'or 1921.\nAndrew Alexander\nSixth Avenue 548 fifth Ave.\nCorner I9?S? Above 45? Sr\nSound Values in\nShoes for the Family\nAT these great stores devoted to shoes\nexclusively, two dollars to-day buys\nwhat three dollars did last spring.\nRevisions to replacement costs were made\nmonths ago. Our Spring stocks are brim\nming over with new merchandise made at\nthe present cost-level, and priced as low, we\nbelieve, as equally good shoes can be for\nsome years to come.\n\nPHOSPHATE ROCK IN TEXAS;\nBED MAY BE 25 MILES WIDE\nHuge Deposits Discovered Indicate Supply Will Prove\n(Greater Than Anywhere Else in the World?Sam\nples Tested Show High Commercial Value.\n?V ii U*t patch to Tii* Saw Voik Untto.\nAt'im.y, Tex.. March 23.?What may\nprove to be an enormous bed of phos\nphate rtx k hfi? been discovered in\nTexas. and an analysis of the samples\nshows tt to be of high commercial value.\nKor many years geologists have been\n?N.'irchJng for phosphate In this State,\nbut none was found until a few days*\n.go, when a thick bed wai encountered\n?..?I ft wildcat oil well that was being\ndrilled twenty miles west of Han An\ntonio. This stratum Is only forty feet be\nlow the surface.\nSamples wore sent to the bureau of\ngeology of the University of Texas for\ntesting, and they proved to be phos\nphate. According to Dr. A. Udden,\ndirector of the bureau, the formation\nwhich contains this phosphate extends\nfrom a point near Waco to the Rio\ni >rande. a distance of about 350 miles,\nand has a width of Ave to twenty-live\nmiles.\nWhile It is not as yet definitely known\nhow thick the deposit is, the test so\nfar made shows that It extends to a\ngreat depth and that the supply of phos\nOIL MEN PREDICT\nBETTER BUSINESS\nLower Freight Rates Urged at\nPetroleum Congress.\nKansas Citt, March 23.?Increased\nprosperity of the ott business was pre\ndicted by speakers to-day before the\nannual meeting of the National Petro\nleum Congress.\nLester Colby, editor of a Chicago pe\ntroleum publication, declared many re\ntailers and Jobbers had been holding off\nbuying gasolene, hoping for further re\nductions in the price of crude oil. These\ndealers, he said, now fear a possible\ngasolene shortage next summer and\nwere flooding the refineries with orders,\nJack N'ours\"? of Kansas City spoke along\nsimilar lines.\nClifford Thorne of Chicago, general\ncounsel for the American Independent\nI'etroleum Association, urged that ef\nforts be made to obtain lower freight\nrates for petroleum products.\nIn this connection he quoted from re\ncent figures of the Federal Bureau of\nExplosives and declared that proportlon\netely the accident rate from gasolene\nis low.\nForty times the quantity of gasolene\nis carried on the railroads as of other\nrecognized explosives, he said, while the\nproperty loss caused by gasolene explo\nsions Is only twenty-seven times and the\ndeath rate only twenty times that caused\nby otlier explosive commodities.\nBUBBER PLANTS TO STAY SHUT.\nW oonsocket 11111m Had Planned to\nKesume lu April.\nWoo.vsocket, K. I.. March 23.?Be\ncause of lack of orders, the Alice Mills\nand th? MUlville (Mass.) plant of the\nWoonsocket Rubber Company, footwear\ndivision of the United States Rubber\nCompany, will not reopen In April, as\noriginally intended, says an announce\nment to-dsy. Operations may not be re\named until six or eight weeks later,\naccording to officials.\nIn the meantime the small force which\nhs< been on duty will be further r<\nduced. About 2,50u persons are err.\n1 ployed normally in tbe two plants. The\nI Alice Mills closed February 19 and the\nMlllvllle plant December 10.\ni>!>ae rook available prouably Is greater\nthan in found anywlwrn in the world.\nOr. rdden says the big significance of\nthe discovery, uslde rrom its commer\ncial Importance, to that the phosphate\niA round in eocene formation, and that\nit Is the only instance so far known\nin the United States of phosphate extst\nj lag in that formation. It is the same\ni geological condition, however, that ex\nists in the French possession of north\nern Africa, where an enormous bod of\nphosphate is betn?; worked.\nImmediate steps will be taken to de\ntermine the extent of the deposit in\nTexas and to mine the rock on an ex\ntensive sale it Is stated. The fact that\nthe stratum is only forty feet below the\nsurface makes It an easy and choap min\ning project, as the overlying earth can\nl?- stripped by means of steam shovels.\nL'p to this time the phosphate fer\ntilizers which are lined in Texas have\ncome chiefly from Florida and Tennes\nsee. With the development of the newly\ndiscovered deposit not only wl\". ths\nhomo demand be supplied but it ia\nprobable there will bo big quantities\navailable for export and shipment to\nother States, it Is asserted.\nBRING PEACE, AID TRADE,\nBARUCH URGES CHICAGO\nGet Squarely Behind Presi\ndent, Says Financier.\nSptr-iai Despatch to Thw Xbw Yci*k ilKtuui.\nChicaoo, March 33.?\"There is one\nquick way to bring: about normal con\nditions. That ia to bring about a cessa\ntlon of the quarrels in Kurope. (ret\ni everybody back to work. Then our\ntrading will increase.'\"\nThis was the message that Bernard\nHaruch, formerly chairman of the War\nIndustries Board, brought with him to\nChicago from New York to-day.\n\"We Should get squarely b?hin3\nPresident Harding and the present Ad\nministration. It Is up to the President\nand the Senate to let Americans step In\nI find help settle things abroad.\" lie\nadded.\n\"Lending money on the part of\nAmerica to European countries Ik very\nnice, but unless wo do something to\nbring about world peace and increase\nI foreign trading we will not make the\n1 world financially s-afe.\"\nMINERS ACCEPT AWARD\nBY ALABAMA GOVERNOR\nU. M. W. Agrees Union Rec\nognition Isn't Obligatory.\nBniMiisrrm *m, Ala.. March 38.?I'nion\n1 coal miners will abide by the awa rt of\n(3ov. Kllby handed down tiatur<*ty Van\ni A. Bittner, representative of the United\nVline Work-rs of America, announced\nj t>ern to-nijrht.\nHis statomeM was r^arded a* tha\nfirst authortta.tive utterance by ^'pre\nventatives of the miners \"n tbe award\nI made by the Governor a it *ole arbiter\nI in tbe Alabama strike, which held that\nrecognition of the union wai not obliga\ntory upon coal operators, and that tlie\nI day wage scale and sub-rontraot sys\ntetn were to remain unchanged.\nA special conwntttee cnosen Bjr John\nfv. L/e*ia, president of the international\nunion, will come here soon Mr. Uittner\nMaid no step* have been taken yet In\nregard to the support of former strikers\nand thoir families.\nHAYS ASKS MAILING\nAT EARLIER HOURS\nTelegraph* Postman ten to\nPress Campaign Among\nBusinesn Men.\nIS SPEEDING I P 8ERVICE\nWould Remove Peak at End\nof Day That Clo^s All\nPost Offices.\nUpriioi Despatch to Tlta N?w Yr??:\nNmr York flrralil Hnrrau. I\nWellington. I>. C., M?r?h S3.\nPostmaster-Oeneral Hays got into\ntelegraphic communication with the\nleading post office* of the country to- j\nday to learn what ran be done In every j\none of then to prevent huge quantities\nof mail being dumped Into the po.v of\nfices within the few hours that follow j\nthe business day, creating a ?euk mall\nins period which clog* the postal ma-\nchlnery and delays the mail.\nHe wants postmasters to wt.irt a cam-;\npalgn among: Chamber* of Comcieree,\nHoards of Trade, merchants and .nanu- j\nfacturers, associations and other*! to,\nsend their mall to the post orflceg\nearlier in the day.\nThe oituation Mr. Hays found In\nWashington, where six-sevenths ot th?\niiay's accumulation of mall is deposited\nin Lite throe hours between ar;d 7\nI'. M., exists in virtually all bettlone of i\nthe country, according to the repli<f>\nwhich so far have reached the Po.-t Of\nfice Department. Each situation Will be\nhandled ax the fact* warrant and a\ngreat effort will be made to have all bufrf\nness men turn their mail over to the\npout offices much earlier In the day.\nMr. Hays sent a circular letter to tlio\nmembers of the Senate and House call-\ning their attention to the situation,\nwhich he explained to President Harding\nand the Cabinet yesterday, that most of'\nthe Washington mail in deposited in the j\nlate afternoon and early evening. The\nCabinet members have agreed to co\noperate, and he wants the members of\nCongress to do the same.\nIt Is Mr. Hays's belief that there will\nbe little difficulty in working out this\narrangement, once it is understood. The\nend of the day naturally i? the time for\nsigning letters, but it is his Idea that\ntime would be saved if the mall that is\nnot signed by executives, such {is form\nletters. booklets and documents of all\nkinds, were sent to the Host Office dur\ning and not after the business day.\nThat !s the chief reform Mr. Hays is\nj working on at this time for the improve\nI ment of the postal service, but he feels\nj at the name time that greater efficiency\nwill result from his programme of \"hu-\nmanlzlng\" the department. There are I\n300,000 employes in the postal service.\nOut In none of the larjte offices even are 1\nI there any recreation or rest room*, such\nI as there are In modern manufacturing\nplants.\nFISHERMEN'S STRIKE ENDS.\nl.*lif Hrlf Worker* Agree to Ac\ncept I#I9 Scnde,\ni CMDVK1.AJTO, March 23. The strike of I\nbake Hrte fishermen, which has been\nIt, progress stn.'e the fishing season\nopened several days ago, was settled\ni \\c-dav at a conference between repre\nsentative* of the fishermen and the\nj Fresh Water Fish Producers' Assocla\nj on.\nI The workers agreed to accent a j\n1 day, the 1P19 scale, it was said. They!\nt.ud demanded a dollar more.\nB\n(oi\n\nfranklin Stmon a Co.\ntA Store of Individual Shops\nFIFTH AVENUE, 37th and 38th STS.\nHigh Qolors ^Measure\nThe Height of Fashion in\nmisses' Tweed suits\nThat Bring The Brightness\nOf The Qottntry Into Town\nOr Take The Smartness Of\nThe Avenue'''' Into t he Country\nThh first lilac blossoms.\nthe first timid green, the\nspring blue of the sky\nFashion weaves her morn\ning colors into primitive\ntextiles, and models them\ninto suits as young as youth.\nlight in weight, bright in\ncolor, right for now ?lilac.\nspring green, French blue,\nplumage, tan, or rust\n39.\n50\nOther Tweed Suits For Misses 2V.S0 to 98.S(J\nSizes y to 20 years\nMISSES' St I I SHOP? Second l:loot\n\"A Regular\nCamel for Ink?\nGoes a Month Without a Drink!\"\nSTICK the end of the marvelous DUNN\nPEN into the ink?pump it full in a\njiffy with the Little Red Pump-HaiKile?\nand forget about it for a month!\nNo other self-filling pen in the world\nholds half as much ink as a DUNN-PEN\nof the same size, simply because other\npens have narrow-chested rubber sac ink\nreservoirs. The average rubber sac is only\nthe diameter of a common lead pencil, and\naside from its small capacity and the\nconstant bother of filling it, it gives end\nless trouble by rotting arid leaking.\n^ze marvelous\nDIM-PEN\nThe Fountain Pen with\nthe Little Red Pump-Handle\nThe DUNN-PEN literally\nholds a full \"barrel\" of ink. It\nhas no valves, springs or levers\nto take up ink space and get out\nof order?it has no seams to leak.\nIt consists of four major parts\nall made with the accuracy of a\nchronometer. From cap to point,\nthe DUNN-PEN is 